title: For Sale:  Colt U.S. Army Model 1917 double action revolver
postcontent: The military serial number on the butt (8096) indicates that this gun was part of the first standard production lot, shipped to Springfield Armory on November 27, 1917. Developed during WWI to supplement 1911 auto pistol production, the Colt Model 1917 is based on the New Service double action revolver modified to chamber the same .45 ACP cartridge used by the Colt Automatic. Loading and ejection are fast using spring steel "moon clips" to hold the cartridges. This early gun has the bored through cylinder chambers so the moon clips are a must. It wears the standard 5-1/2" barrel that is "UNITED STATES PROPERTY" marked along the bottom. This revolver was overhauled at some point between the World Wars and was reblued (before Parkerizing became the standard). The frame, yoke, cylinder and ejector assembly have been arsenal numbered to match although the original Colt factory serial number is also matching inside the frame and yoke. Overall condition is good, with some finish loss and spotting from a chemical spill (or possibly blood) as well as some thinning to the grip straps. There are some handling marks but no significant pitting. The brown plastic grips feature silver Colt medallions and are likely WWII or post-war replacements. The revolver functions alright although there is some play between the frame and yoke when at rest. Lock-up is good with the trigger held to the rear. The timing is slightly late in single action but works perfectly fired double action. The bore is very good with strong rifling that is light frosted (but free of deep pitting). A well worn black stained 1917-dated U.S. holster is included.

title: For Sale:  SMITH & WESSON - Model 16-4 -- .32 MAGNUM....8-3/8 Barrel...Rare Gun, LNIB
postcontent: Here's a rather rare Smith & Wesson revolver. This is a Model 16-4. Chambered for the .32 Magnum, this revolver sports the 8-3/8" full-lug barrel. The Model 16-4 was introduced in 1989 but was only made for a few years. A total of just 8800 guns were manufactured in three barrel lengths: 4", 6" and 8-3/8" with the long barrel being the least common of all. This revolver is in excellent, like new condition. The original blue finish rates virtually 100% with a faint cylinder turn line being the only visible wear. The original finger groove wood "combat" style grips are excellent. The target hammer and target trigger both have nice bright case colors. The mechanics are in perfect working order and the bore is perfect as well. Comes in the original box that numbers to the gun and included are the owner's manual, cleaning kit and miscellaneous paperwork. This is an extremely nice and very hard to find Smith

I have a Remington 870 that has been setup for deer hunting. It has a fully rifled cantilevered slug barrel. It has the Remington Sure Shot stock, Burris Fullfield 3-9x40 with ballistic reticle (not pictured), and Timney trigger kit. For those of you who don't know Timney makes a kit for the 870 to correct creep and heavy trigger pull. It is currently setup with a 3lb trigger. I have the other weight springs to go with it along with the original raised comb stock and Limbsaver recoil pad. I shoot Remington 2-3/4 Accutip slugs with amazing accuracy. You can barely buy the parts for what I'm asking for the gun. There is minimal wear on the gun as it's only used a few days a year. I'm selling to fund a custom muzzleloader build. $450 for the package or $350 minus the scope and rings. I have all the boxes and manuals.

postcontent:
You may never find one of these for sale, mint in the box ever again!
This is a rare Daisy Softair Model 12 airsoft gun. This was the beginning of the airsoft craze. These were manufactured in 1988 and only made about 1 year before they were pulled from the shelves for being almost identical looking of the guns they were made to resemble. It uses actual shells to hold the softair bb’s, which, when fired eject from the gun just like a real firearm. It does use the standard airsoft bb’s of today, so if you still want to use it there is no shortage of ammo. Resembles the Tec-9.

Hard to find AND complete, unused, and in the original box!!!
This originally sold for $69.99 back in 1988, so it wasn’t a cheap toy.
Excellent condition with the exception of the box top left corner has a slightly small wrinkle (see pic) and some minor shekve wear. Cash on pickup. Postal MO if shipped.
